spec: socket_extra110
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(socket)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/socket.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/socket.html — Python socket module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-10"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/socket.py"
    - "CPython source: Modules/socketmodule.c"
    - "socket_extra109.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.socket Python-defined method co_argcount values — close, makefile, accept, detach (all have __code__); socket.socket.__init__ co_argcount; method qualnames for close/makefile/accept/detach/__init__; type names for Python-level socket methods (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra108.zspec.zsdl — covers gethostname/gethostbyname/getnameinfo C-level identity / getaddrinfo/getfqdn Python-level identity / setdefaulttimeout/getdefaulttimeout C-level / create_connection Python-level / getfqdn code attributes (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra107.zspec.zsdl — covers socket SO_* option constants class names and integer values / socket.error and socket.timeout class identity and MRO (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra106.zspec.zsdl — covers IPPROTO_TCP/UDP/IP/ICMP/IPV6 class names and values / SOL_SOCKET class name and value (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra105.zspec.zsdl — covers AF_*/SOCK_* class module/qualname/mro / AddressFamily/SocketKind name/module/metaclass/base identity (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra104.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.socket C-method types / socket.socket method qualname lengths / socket.socket Python-level method types and class identity (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra103.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.inet_aton/ntoa/pton/ntop class names and qualname lengths / htons/htonl/ntohs/ntohl class names / herror/gaierror MRO depth / AddressFamily/SocketKind MRO depth (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra102.zspec.zsdl — covers socket.socket __qualname__/__name__.__len__()==6 / error/__name__.__eq__('OSError') / herror/gaierror qualname/module/bases / AddressFamily/SocketKind qualname lengths and module (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra99.zspec.zsdl — covers socket module-level function qualname lengths / SocketIO class metaclass/module/bases (table + invariants)."
    - "socket_extra96.zspec.zsdl — covers AF_INET/AF_UNIX/AF_INET6/AF_UNSPEC and SOCK_STREAM/SOCK_DGRAM/SOCK_RAW class names / AddressFamily/SocketKind __bases__ (table + invariants)."
  notes:
    - "This spec extends socket through socket_extra109; it does NOT duplicate invariants present in those files."
    - "Wave 271 theme: socket.socket __enter__ and __exit__ context manager methods — both are Python functions with qualnames 'socket.__enter__' and 'socket.__exit__'; __enter__ co_argcount==1, __exit__ co_argcount==1; socket.socket.__repr__ is a Python function; socket.socket.fileno is a method_descriptor; socket.socket.__module__=='socket' and __qualname__=='socket'."
    - "type(socket.socket.__enter__).__name__ == 'function'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__ == 'socket.__enter__'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__enter__.__code__.co_argcount == 1. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "type(socket.socket.__exit__).__name__ == 'function'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__ == 'socket.__exit__'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount == 1. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__enter__.__code__.co_name == '__enter__'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__exit__.__code__.co_name == '__exit__'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len('socket.__enter__') == 16. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len('socket.__exit__') == 15. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "type(socket.socket.__repr__).__name__ == 'function'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__repr__.__qualname__ == 'socket.__repr__'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__repr__.__code__.co_argcount == 1. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len('socket.__repr__') == 15. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__module__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.__qualname__ == 'socket'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len(socket.socket.__qualname__) == 6. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len(socket.socket.__module__) == 6. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "type(socket.socket.fileno).__name__ == 'method_descriptor'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "socket.socket.fileno.__qualname__ == 'socket.fileno'. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "len('socket.fileno') == 13. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "Note: socket.socket.__enter__ and __exit__ are Python-defined functions in Lib/socket.py implementing the context manager protocol. __enter__ returns self; __exit__ calls self.close(). Both have co_argcount==1 even though __exit__ is defined with 4 parameters (self, *args) — because the *args are var-positional (not counted in co_argcount). Wait: co_argcount is 1 because __exit__ has signature __exit__(self, *args) — the *args parameters are counted in co_varargcount, not co_argcount. Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0."
    - "Note: socket.socket.fileno is a method_descriptor (C-level method from _socket.socket) even though socket.socket is a Python class. fileno() returns the underlying OS file descriptor as an integer. The C-level fileno is inherited from _socket.socket via MRO. This distinguishes fileno from Python-defined methods like close, accept, makefile, __enter__, __exit__ which are 'function' type."
    - "Note: socket_extra102 anchors socket.socket.__qualname__.__len__()==6; socket_extra104 anchors Python-level method types; socket_extra109 anchors close/accept/makefile/detach/__init__ qualname equality. This spec anchors __enter__/__exit__ context manager methods for the first time."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-10."
  created_at: "2026-04-10T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# type(socket.socket.__enter__).__name__.__eq__('function')
# socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__enter__')
# socket.socket.__enter__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__(1)
# type(socket.socket.__exit__).__name__.__eq__('function')
# socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__exit__')
#
# Wave 271 theme: socket.socket __enter__ and __exit__ are Python functions.
#
# socket.socket.__enter__ and __exit__ implement the context manager protocol
# for the socket class. Both are Python-defined functions in Lib/socket.py.
# __enter__ returns self (allows 'with socket() as s:' usage). __exit__ calls
# self.close() with *args. Both have co_argcount==1 (self only; __exit__'s
# additional parameters are *args in co_varargcount). socket_extra109 anchors
# close/accept qualname equality; this spec anchors __enter__/__exit__ for first time.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table socket_extra110.socket_enter_and_exit_type_qualname_argcount:
  description: "type(socket.__enter__).__name__.__eq__('function')==True / socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__enter__')==True / socket.__enter__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__(1)==True / type(socket.__exit__).__name__.__eq__('function')==True / socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__exit__')==True — __enter__ and __exit__ implement context manager protocol; both are Python functions in Lib/socket.py; both have co_argcount==1; __enter__ returns self; __exit__ calls close(); extra109 anchors close/accept; first sockctx110 anchor"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: method_identity
  id_prefix: sockctx110

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [enter_type_fn,        "socket.__enter__.__class__.__name__.__eq__",         ["function"],          true, "type(socket.__enter__) is 'function' (Python-defined in Lib/socket.py; implements context manager entry)"]
    - [enter_qualname_eq,    "socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__",               ["socket.__enter__"],  true, "socket.__enter__.__qualname__ is 'socket.__enter__' (16 chars; 'socket.'=7 + '__enter__'=9)"]
    - [enter_co_argcount,    "socket.__enter__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__",       [1],                   true, "socket.__enter__.__code__.co_argcount is 1 (only 'self'; __enter__ returns self for 'with socket() as s:')"]
    - [exit_type_fn,         "socket.__exit__.__class__.__name__.__eq__",          ["function"],          true, "type(socket.__exit__) is 'function' (Python-defined in Lib/socket.py; implements context manager exit)"]
    - [exit_qualname_eq,     "socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__",                ["socket.__exit__"],   true, "socket.__exit__.__qualname__ is 'socket.__exit__' (15 chars; 'socket.'=7 + '__exit__'=8)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__(1)
# socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__len__()==16
# socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__len__()==15
# socket.socket.__repr__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__repr__')
# type(socket.socket.__repr__).__name__.__eq__('function')
#
# Wave 271 theme: __exit__ co_argcount, qualname lengths, __repr__ identity.
#
# socket.socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount is 1. Although __exit__(self, *args)
# appears to take 4 arguments, co_argcount only counts positional-or-keyword
# parameters; the *args are in co_varargcount (1). So co_argcount==1 (self only).
# socket.__enter__ qualname is 16 chars, __exit__ is 15 chars (one less because
# '__exit__' is 8 chars vs '__enter__' is 9 chars). socket.__repr__ is also a
# Python function with qualname 'socket.__repr__' (15 chars).
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table socket_extra110.socket_exit_argcount_qualname_lens_repr_identity:
  description: "socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__(1)==True / socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__len__()==16 / socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__len__()==15 / socket.__repr__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__repr__')==True / type(socket.__repr__).__name__.__eq__('function')==True — __exit__ has co_argcount==1 (*args are in co_varargcount); __enter__ is 16 chars, __exit__ is 15 chars (one less: '__enter__'=9 vs '__exit__'=8); __repr__ is Python function with qualname 'socket.__repr__'; first sockctx110 anchor"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: method_identity
  id_prefix: sockctx110

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [exit_co_argcount,     "socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount.__eq__",        [1],                   true, "socket.__exit__.__code__.co_argcount is 1 (*args is co_varargcount; co_argcount counts positional-or-keyword only)"]
    - [enter_qualname_len,   "socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__len__",               [],                    16,   "socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__len__() is 16 ('socket.__enter__': 'socket.'=7 + '__enter__'=9)"]
    - [exit_qualname_len,    "socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__len__",                [],                    15,   "socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__len__() is 15 ('socket.__exit__': 'socket.'=7 + '__exit__'=8; one less than __enter__)"]
    - [repr_qualname_eq,     "socket.__repr__.__qualname__.__eq__",                 ["socket.__repr__"],   true, "socket.__repr__.__qualname__ is 'socket.__repr__' (15 chars; same length as __exit__ qualname)"]
    - [repr_type_fn,         "socket.__repr__.__class__.__name__.__eq__",           ["function"],          true, "type(socket.__repr__) is 'function' (Python-defined __repr__ in Lib/socket.py; formats socket info string)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.__module__.__eq__('socket')
# socket.socket.__qualname__.__eq__('socket')
# socket.socket.__qualname__.__len__()==6
# socket.socket.__module__.__len__()==6
# type(socket.socket.fileno).__name__.__eq__('method_descriptor')
#
# Wave 271 theme: socket.socket class identity and fileno method type.
#
# socket.socket.__module__ is 'socket' (6 chars) and socket.socket.__qualname__
# is 'socket' (6 chars). Both __qualname__ and __module__ have the same length
# (6) — the class is named 'socket' (lowercase) and lives in the 'socket' module.
# socket.socket.fileno is a method_descriptor (C-level method inherited from
# _socket.socket) with qualname 'socket.fileno' (13 chars). socket_extra102
# anchors socket.socket.__qualname__.__len__()==6; this spec anchors the __module__
# and full __qualname__ equality plus fileno type as a grouped table.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table socket_extra110.socket_class_module_qualname_and_fileno_type:
  description: "socket.__module__.__eq__('socket')==True / socket.__qualname__.__eq__('socket')==True / socket.__qualname__.__len__()==6 / socket.__module__.__len__()==6 / type(socket.fileno).__name__.__eq__('method_descriptor')==True — socket class has __module__=='socket' (6 chars) and __qualname__=='socket' (6 chars; lowercase class name); both lengths equal 6; fileno is method_descriptor (C-level from _socket.socket); extra102 anchors __qualname__ length; first sockctx110 anchor"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: class_identity
  id_prefix: sockctx110

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [module_eq,            "socket.__module__.__eq__",                     ["socket"],             true, "socket.socket.__module__ is 'socket' (6 chars; the Python socket module in Lib/socket.py)"]
    - [qualname_eq,          "socket.__qualname__.__eq__",                   ["socket"],             true, "socket.socket.__qualname__ is 'socket' (6 chars; lowercase class name; top-level class in socket module)"]
    - [qualname_len,         "socket.__qualname__.__len__",                  [],                     6,    "socket.socket.__qualname__.__len__() is 6 ('socket': 6 chars; same as __module__ length)"]
    - [module_len,           "socket.__module__.__len__",                    [],                     6,    "socket.socket.__module__.__len__() is 6 ('socket': 6 chars; same as __qualname__ length)"]
    - [fileno_type_eq,       "socket.fileno.__class__.__name__.__eq__",      ["method_descriptor"],  true, "type(socket.fileno) is 'method_descriptor' (C-level from _socket.socket; contrast with Python-defined close/accept)"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# type(socket.socket.__enter__).__name__.__eq__('function') — standalone
#
# type(socket.socket.__enter__).__name__ is 'function'. socket.socket.__enter__
# is defined in Lib/socket.py as a Python function that implements the context
# manager protocol entry. When used with 'with socket.socket() as s:', Python
# calls __enter__ which returns self (the socket instance), binding it to 's'.
# The function type confirms this is a Python-defined method, not a C-level
# method_descriptor like fileno or send/recv. socket_extra109 anchors Python-
# level method types (close, accept, etc.); this spec anchors __enter__ type
# as a standalone for context manager protocol under sockctx110.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant socket_extra110.socket_enter_is_function:
  description: "type(socket.socket.__enter__).__name__.__eq__('function') == True — __enter__ is Python-defined in Lib/socket.py (implements context manager entry; returns self); function type (not method_descriptor/wrapper_descriptor); enables 'with socket() as s:' pattern; extra109 anchors Python-level method types; first standalone for __enter__ under sockctx110"
  category: method_identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "socket.__enter__.__class__.__name__.__eq__"
  args: ["function"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__enter__') — standalone
#
# socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__ is 'socket.__enter__' (16 chars: 'socket.'=7 +
# '__enter__'=9). This is the longest qualname among socket.socket Python-defined
# context manager methods — __enter__ qualname (16) is one char longer than
# __exit__ (15) because '__enter__' has 9 chars vs '__exit__' with 8 chars.
# The qualname follows the 'socket.method' pattern used by all Python-defined
# socket.socket methods. socket_extra109 anchors close/accept/makefile/detach/
# __init__ qualnames; this spec anchors __enter__ qualname equality as a standalone.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant socket_extra110.socket_enter_qualname_eq:
  description: "socket.socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__enter__') == True — qualname is 'socket.__enter__' (16 chars; 'socket.'=7 + '__enter__'=9); longest context manager method qualname (16 > __exit__=15); follows 'socket.method' pattern; extra109 anchors other Python-defined method qualnames; first standalone for __enter__ qualname under sockctx110"
  category: method_identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "socket.__enter__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["socket.__enter__"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__exit__') — standalone
#
# socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__ is 'socket.__exit__' (15 chars: 'socket.'=7 +
# '__exit__'=8). socket.__exit__ is the context manager exit method defined in
# Lib/socket.py. It calls self.close() after the 'with' block, ensuring the
# socket is closed even if an exception occurs. The *args signature allows
# __exit__ to receive the exception type, value, and traceback (or None, None,
# None on success) without explicitly naming them. The qualname length (15)
# matches socket.__repr__ (also 15 chars). No prior socket spec anchors
# socket.__exit__ qualname equality as a standalone under sockctx110.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant socket_extra110.socket_exit_qualname_eq:
  description: "socket.socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.__exit__') == True — qualname is 'socket.__exit__' (15 chars; 'socket.'=7 + '__exit__'=8); calls self.close() after 'with' block; *args signature accepts exc_type/exc_val/exc_tb (or None); co_argcount==1 (*args in co_varargcount); length 15 matches socket.__repr__; no prior spec anchors as standalone; first standalone under sockctx110"
  category: method_identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "socket.__exit__.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["socket.__exit__"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.fileno.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.fileno') — standalone
#
# socket.socket.fileno.__qualname__ is 'socket.fileno' (13 chars: 'socket.'=7 +
# 'fileno'=6). fileno is a C-level method_descriptor inherited from _socket.socket.
# It returns the underlying OS file descriptor as an integer. The fact that fileno
# is method_descriptor (not 'function') distinguishes it from Python-defined socket
# methods like close, accept, __enter__, __exit__. The qualname 'socket.fileno'
# has length 13 — the same as socket.socket.accept qualname (also 13 chars).
# socket_extra104 anchors socket.socket C-method types; this spec anchors
# fileno qualname equality as a standalone under sockctx110.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant socket_extra110.socket_fileno_qualname_eq:
  description: "socket.socket.fileno.__qualname__.__eq__('socket.fileno') == True — qualname is 'socket.fileno' (13 chars; 'socket.'=7 + 'fileno'=6); C-level method_descriptor from _socket.socket (not Python-defined function); returns OS file descriptor int; qualname length 13 matches socket.accept; extra104 anchors C-method types; first standalone for fileno qualname under sockctx110"
  category: method_identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "socket.fileno.__qualname__.__eq__"
  args: ["socket.fileno"]
  expected: true

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# socket.socket.__module__.__eq__('socket') — standalone
#
# socket.socket.__module__ is 'socket'. The socket class is defined in Lib/socket.py
# as the Python-level wrapper around _socket.socket. Its __module__ attribute is
# 'socket' — the name of the module where the class is defined. This is consistent
# with socket.socket.__qualname__ which is also 'socket' (6 chars each). The
# lowercase name 'socket' for both the module and the class can be confusing;
# 'socket.socket' refers to the class named 'socket' inside the 'socket' module.
# socket_extra102 anchors socket.socket.__qualname__.__len__()==6; no prior
# socket spec anchors socket.socket.__module__ equality as a standalone.
# Verified Python 3.14.3 macOS/Darwin 25.4.0.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant socket_extra110.socket_class_module_eq:
  description: "socket.socket.__module__.__eq__('socket') == True — socket class __module__ is 'socket' (6 chars; defined in Lib/socket.py); both __module__ and __qualname__ are 'socket' (same 6-char string); lowercase 'socket' class in 'socket' module; extra102 anchors __qualname__ length; first standalone for __module__ equality under sockctx110"
  category: class_identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: "socket.__module__.__eq__"
  args: ["socket"]
  expected: true
